    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3436464619" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3436464619" />
    <a title="Noel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/86486355-noel"><img alt="Noel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627517508p2/86486355.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3436464619?book_show_action=true">May 02, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Noel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Noel" href="/user/show/86486355-noel">Noel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/86486355-noel?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3436464619" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15100959939204281435"><i>“That reminder brought me straight to her. She was as open and trusting with me as ever, but her expression was very sad, and as she sat in her poor house, gazing out over the dewy garden and crying in concert with the crickets’ lament, I felt as though I must be living in some old tale.”</i><br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1619968440i/31271035._SY540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/>Illustration of a chapter of the novel, by Tosa Mitsuyoshi (17th century).<br/><br/>The young man has never been here before. He hears the rustling of silks and women’s laughter. (What could it be about?) He makes his way</span>
  <span id="freeText15100959939204281435" style="display:none"><i>“That reminder brought me straight to her. She was as open and trusting with me as ever, but her expression was very sad, and as she sat in her poor house, gazing out over the dewy garden and crying in concert with the crickets’ lament, I felt as though I must be living in some old tale.”</i><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1619968440i/31271035._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>Illustration of a chapter of the novel, by Tosa Mitsuyoshi (17th century).<br><br>The young man has never been here before. He hears the rustling of silks and women’s laughter. (What could it be about?) He makes his way softly to a crack he finds in the shutters. A blind rattles; he stops for a moment, his heart pounding, but no one seems to have noticed. He peers through the crack and sees three women sewing in the lamplight. Then he sees <i>her</i>, the girl he had seen that night, also by lamplight—it has to be! She lies with her head pillowed on her arm, gazing into the light, her hair spilling down over her forehead. Her whole figure stirs troubled yearnings in him.<br><br>As we judge him for his voyeurism, we realize we are watchers as well, peering through curtains, screens, and sliding doors into a distant, vanished world. And like him, we fall hopelessly in love.<br><br>* * *<br><br>Around this time last year, when the plague swept across continents and the world seemed to be coming to an end, I was looking for a new book to read. I can’t remember what me decide on this ancient Japanese novel, but with all the time I was spending at home, I figured I could finish it in a month or two—over the summer before fall classes began. Ha! I couldn’t have been more wrong.<br><br>For a long time, there was no greater comfort than lying in bed in the lamplight and returning to this world of romance and intrigue. But as it often happens with long books, I began to grow restless. This novel has hundreds of characters (only ever referred to by titles and honorifics, which are constantly changing), and it has <i>nothing</i> resembling a plot. I was certain this book would never end. I began to wonder if I’d made a mistake, but it was too late! I was already melting under the soft caresses of Stockholm syndrome. I was going to finish this book. A year later, and I finally have. I’ve been waiting for this moment for so long, but I don’t feel as proud of myself as I thought I would be. Mostly, I just feel hopelessly sad: the characters I’ve come to know over a thousand pages are gone.<br><br><i>“He felt her there beside him, just as she had always been on evenings like this when he had called for music, and when her touch on her instrument, or her least word to him, had been so much her own; except that he would have preferred even to this vivid dream her simple reality in the dark.”</i><br><br>The Tale of Genji was written in early-11th-century Japan by Murasaki Shikibu, a court lady who lived during the Heian period. It’s often said to be the world’s first novel (which isn’t exactly true, but I don’t think it matters). The Tale of Genji is remarkable in its realism and psychological depth, and it’s told with an almost unearthly beauty and grace; it doesn’t seem to be of this world. Murasaki’s hero, Hikaru Genji, is not a warrior (as you might expect), and he’s certainly not a samurai (those would only appear in literature hundreds of years later). Instead, he’s a man of the arts, the illegitimate son of the emperor, and more than anything, a lover. The romantic pursuits of Casanova seem to pale in comparison. We follow his life and many loves as he rises through the ranks of the Imperial Court.<br><br><i>“The sight of her lying there, so beautiful yet so thin and weak that she hardly seemed among the living, aroused his love and his keenest sympathy. The hair streaming across her pillow, not a strand out of place, struck him as a wonder, and as he gazed at her, he found himself unable to understand how for all these years he could have seen any flaw in her.”</i><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1619968440i/31271036._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>From an album of scenes from the novel, by Tosa Mitsunori (17th century).<br><br>The novel centers on life’s three eternals: love, lust, and loss—but mostly love. In Heian Japan, men and women were rarely allowed to see each other clearly. Women sat hidden behind screens and curtains, and all it took was a man seeing a woman’s sleeves spilling from under the blinds to fall madly in love with her. Most of the novel still resonates today, although there are parts that make for… uncomfortable reading. Men in the novel often force themselves on women. Some of these encounters are portrayed as romantic, but many are portrayed as horrific. The Tale of Genji is less about the men in the story than the women they surround themselves with—“their feelings, their experiences, their fates,” as Royall Tyler says in the introduction—and one of the most fascinating things about the novel is how Murasaki reveals the unfair lives they have to lead in their oppressively patriarchal world, despite the poems on scented paper or the gorgeous robes they may receive.<br><br><i>“Ah, she reflected, there is nothing so pitifully confined and constricted as a woman. What will reward her passage through the world if she remains sunk in herself, blind to life’s joys and sorrows and to every delight? What will brighten the monotony of her fleeting days? […] What a waste for her to shut herself up in her thoughts….”</i><br><br>The Tale of Genji is often compared to In Search of Lost Time, a comparison that hardly seems worth taking seriously at first, but the similarities really are striking. Both novels try to capture all of life in their words; they’re social and cultural portraits of their time, interwoven with their protagonists’ transition from childhood to adulthood. Both reveal the inner lives of their characters with great sensitivity and perception, and have a way of making you stop to notice things about the world—the beauty of every flower, the song of every bird. And both novels deal so often with nostalgia. The great motif of this novel is <i>mono no aware</i>, the awareness of the impermanence of things, that everything and everyone we love is doomed to fade away, like autumn leaves or (of course) cherry blossoms—a short while after they bloom, the slightest breeze sweeps them off their branches. Time passes quickly, leaving only memories behind, and maybe all we can do is to cherish every moment.<br><br><i>“The place was a little way into the mountains. the blossoms in the City were gone now, since it was late in the third month, but in the mountains the cherry trees were in full bloom, and the farther he went, the lovelier the veils of mist became, until for him, whose rank so restricted travel that all this was new, the landscape became a source of wonder.”</i><br><br>The characters in this novel are always longing for the past. The snow, the moonlight, the scent of the blossoms always bring back a flood of memories. I’m still trying to understand why I love books (and films, and music) about memory so much. Maybe it’s because reading a book, especially one as long and all-encompassing as this one, is the closest we’ll ever get to experiencing a whole other life, so the characters’ memories—and all the joy, all the pain they bring—become ours as well. Or maybe it’s because all literature, and all art when you think about it, is ultimately about the past. When something is written, it immediately begins to date, and a thousand years later, all that remains is a gorgeous relic of the way things were—the way people felt, and the way they lived their lives.<br><br><i>“Not that tales accurately describe any particular person, rather, the telling begins when all those things the teller longs to have pass on to future generations—whatever there is about the way people live their lives, for better or worse, that is a sight to see or a wonder to hear—overflow the teller’s heart. […] To put it nicely, there is nothing that does not have its own value.”</i><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1619968440i/31271037._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>Calligraphic excerpt from a chapter of the novel, by Tosa Mitsuyoshi.<br><br>The Tale of Genji is doubtless one of the most beautiful books I’ve ever read, and it’s made its way to my favorites. It’s full of beliefs and practices we may not recognize, that may no longer exist, but its human passions, despairs, and simple joys at being alive are still so familiar; they reach across the ages, and I think that speaks to the constancy of the human heart in our endlessly changing world.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15100959939204281435" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


