        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer366059283" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5908369634339013069">&quot;<i>The Tale of Genji</i> is a novel written by an aristocratic woman for other women of her rank -- men at this time read history and poetry, sometimes theology, but not fiction -- which presents the first challenge to reading it. It wasn&apos;t written for you, dear reader, but for select contemporaries who instinctively understood everything that now needs to be spelled out in annotations and commentary. . . . The modern reader doesn&apos;t so much listen to the story as eavesdrop on it, spy on it, like the c</span>
  <span id="freeText5908369634339013069" style="display:none">"<i>The Tale of Genji</i> is a novel written by an aristocratic woman for other women of her rank -- men at this time read history and poetry, sometimes theology, but not fiction -- which presents the first challenge to reading it. It wasn't written for you, dear reader, but for select contemporaries who instinctively understood everything that now needs to be spelled out in annotations and commentary. . . . The modern reader doesn't so much listen to the story as eavesdrop on it, spy on it, like the courtiers in <i>Genji</i> always peeking through gaps and peepholes to catch glimpses of the young beauties indoors. The reader of <i>Genji</i> is not an invited guest but a voyeur." -- Steven Moore, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7783692.The_Novel_An_Alternative_History_Beginnings_to_1600" title="The Novel An Alternative History Beginnings to 1600 by Steven Moore" rel="nofollow noopener">The Novel: An Alternative History: Beginnings to 1600</a>, p544.</span>
